text: Yeah, so because there's this very limited set of option strategies that you can pursue that involve buying kind of far out of the money options and relying on vol convexity and vol expansion, because that's really the only strategy you can pursue to get that kind of convexity, you get very levered to what your monetization decision is. So if I've got a portfolio of seven to 10 month, one or less delta options, and you get the COVID sell-off, when do you sell them? So essentially, the monetization decision becomes very, very difficult the more you rely on vol expansion and vol convexity as your primary lever of return. Now, you don't have to. I think we're going to talk about later. That's actually a false choice. But if you're going to rely on vol expansion, monetization is a very big concern. And the manager's agency then becomes a very big concern, because they're afraid of selling it too early, because they sell it too early and lock in a gain, particularly if there's an incentive fee. Now, there's this big question of, well, is the manager just there trying to lock in their incentive fee instead of trying to do what is best for the total return of the hedge out? And the manager's definitely afraid of selling it too late. Right? There's nothing worse than having a mark-to-market gain at the end of the month that's then gone by the second week of the next month. So it's just a very hard problem that ultimately is most likely to get resolved by the manager monetizing too much or too quickly.
